huntBios.GENERAL_INFORMATION: This unit is managed as a General Season deer hunt and is not necessarily managed for trophy bucks, but every year a few nice bucks are taken. Hunters should be aware of the Ute Tribal Lands and learn the boundaries. Public hunting is not permitted on Tribal Lands. There are no CWMUs on this unit. The Uintah Mountain range can provide a remote hunt with few hunters but there are also less deer. Much of the habitat in the high country is fairly sterile without much feed for deer. It is generally Lodge Pole Pine without much of an understory. There are several four wheeler roads and dirt roads that provide a lot of access on much of the unit. The Bonanza unit has very low deer densities.
huntBios.SAFETY_CONS: There is spotty cell service in some of the lower elevation hunting areas and typically on the faces overlooking the Uinta Basin. However, there are many areas with no phone service so let someone know where you are going and when you will be back.
huntBios.WEATHER_CONS: The weather on this hunt unit can vary dramatically during the hunting season. Be prepared for warm & dry, or rainy, lightening, windy or snowy conditions. Early snow storms occur often during this hunt. Most of the time snow will melt off within a day or so. Be prepared for muddy or snowy road conditions.
huntBios.MANAGEMENT_OBJ: 100~13000 (includes Diamond Mtn)~9800 (includes Diamond Mtn)~15–17~14.4~~~~~~~~For more detailed information on population and objective data please see the Big Game Annual Report Page.
huntBios.BIOLOGIST_NOTES:
Migration Patterns: Deer on this unit migrate down in elevation for the winter and tend to stay on south facing slopes at lower elevation on the Forest Service lands. Mule Deer rut: This hunt gets close to the the mule deer rut that usually runs from mid Nov.-mid Dec.

Recommended areas in the South Slope, Vernal: There are numerous suggested areas to hunt on this unit. There is a variety of habitat to hunt during this late muzzleloader hunt. There is pinyon/juniper, sage brush savanna, thick lodge pole pine and areas above timber line. The larger openings on the forest are called parks and can be found on most maps but the smaller openings are scattered across the high country. If you choose to hunt the high country, be prepared for unpredictable weather and rocky terrain. During the hunts most of the deer on the unit are found in the habitat belt where aspen mixes with sagebrush and conifer. That zone across the South Slope is the most productive for deer. The suggested areas to hunt include (starting on the west side of the unit: Whiterocks Canyon– Whiterocks River is the western unit boundary, steep terrain. Paradise Park- Higher forest terrain, steep forested canyons. Mosby Mountain- High aspen forest, with large sagebrush bowls, excellent habitat. Red Cloud Loop Rd- Long road that starts in Dry Fork Canyon (west of Vernal). It takes you all the way through the Vernal unit, and comes out on Hwy 191.. Taylor Mountain- Great vantage points. Excellent area to glass and locate animals from far distances. Colton Ranger Station- Aspen/conifer mix forest. Limestone, Little V, and Range Study- These areas are east of Hwy 191 and border the Diamond Mountain limited entry deer and elk unit, know the boundary and your location.

huntMaster.SPECIAL_PROVISIONS: This is a Limited-entry hunt that takes place on a General-season unit. You will lose your bonus points if you draw out for this hunt.

huntMaster.HARVEST_REPORTING: REQUIRED: click here or call 1-800-221-0659 to report your harvest. You must report your harvest, even if you did not take an animal, within 30 days of the season end date that is printed on your permit; failure to do so may result in you not being able to apply for big game species in subsequent years. Submitting teeth or other biological samples from your animal, or having your animal checked by a DWR representative or CWMU operator does NOT fulfill your mandatory harvest reporting requirement.

huntBoundaryInfos.LAND_OWNERSHIP: Public, Private and Tribal Lands.  The public lands include US Forest Service lands managed by the Ashley National Forest and BLM lands.  The Tribal lands are mostly the lower elevation sagebrush areas.  There is a large amount of private property on the unit too.
huntBoundaryInfos.CAMPGRND_INFO:
All Campgrounds on this unit are managed by the US National Forest Service. Camping outside of official campgrounds is also permitted on most of the Forest. Please direct all questions regarding campground availability and other camping questions to the US Forest Service or BLM. Maps and camping regulations are available on their websites.
Ashley National Forest website: http://www.fs.usda.gov/ashley
Vernal BLM website: http://www.blm.gov/ut/st/en/fo/vernal.html
huntBoundaryInfos.SUGGESTED_MAPS: USGS 1:100,000 Dutch John, Vernal, Seep Ridge Topo maps or BLM version equivalent that indentifies land ownership.
huntBoundaryInfos.ATV_VEH_ACCESS:
Travel management on Forest Service and BLM lands in this unit is regulated through federal travel management plans which address road and trail restrictions including use of ATVs. Current information on these travel management plans and maps can be obtained from the Forest Service Ashley National Forest office (435) 789-1181 and Vernal BLM office (435) 781-4400.
Maps can also be purchased online at: http://www.fs.usda.gov/ashley
huntBoundaryInfos.PRIV_TRIBE_LAND_ISSUES: The hunt unit does not include Ute Tribal lands as shown on the hunt boundary map on the Division's website.  There is a large tract of Ute Tribal Trust Land that stretches east to west across the South Slope of the Uinta’s.  Road access across the Tribal land is permitted only across the main access roads to the Forest.  All ATVs are prohibited on Tribal lands they must be trailered on access roads across Tribal Lands.
huntBoundaryInfos.BOUNDARY_DESCRIPTION: Daggett, Duchesne and Uintah counties—Boundary begins at the Utah-Colorado state line and the White River; west along this river to the Green River; north along this river to the Duchesne River; north along this river to the Uinta River; north along this river to Whiterocks river; north along this river to the East Fork of the Whiterocks River; north along this river to Whiterocks Lake and USFS Trail #025; northeast on this trail to the Dry Fork-Whiterocks drainage divide; north atop this divide to the Daggett-Uintah county line (summit of the Uinta Mountains); east along the summit of the Uinta Mountains to US-191; north on US-191 to Cart Creek; north along this creek to Flaming Gorge Reservoir; east along the south shoreline of Flaming Gorge Reservoir to the Green River; east along this river to Gorge Creek; south along Gorge Creek to the USFS/private land boundary at the head of Davenport Draw; south along the USFS/private land boundary on the west side of Davenport Draw to the BLM boundary; south along the BLM boundary approximately one-third of a mile to the rim of Diamond Mountain; south and easterly along this rim until the rim intersects the Diamond Mountain road (Jones Hole Road); southwest on this road to Brush Creek road; south on this road to Island Park road; east on this road to Dinosaur National Monument Boundary; northeast on this monument boundary to the Utah-Colorado state line; south on this state line to the White River. EXCLUDES ALL NATIVE AMERICAN TRUST LANDS WITHIN THIS BOUNDARY. USGS 1:100,000 Maps: Dutch John, Kings Peak, Seep Ridge, Vernal. Boundary questions? Call Vernal office, 435-781-9453.
